# Explicit Types Everywhere

This is a fundamental ground rule. Every piece of TypeScript in this project must be explicitly typed. No exceptions.

## What Must Be Typed

- `const` and `let` declarations
- Function parameters
- Function and method return types
- Class properties and fields
- Arrow functions (parameters and return)
- Destructured variables (type the source or annotate)
- Generic type arguments (never rely on inference for non-obvious types)
- Array/object literals assigned to variables
- Callback parameters (including `subscribe`, `map`, `filter`, etc.)

## Examples

```typescript
// BAD — inferred types
const name = 'Alice';
const items = [1, 2, 3];
let count = 0;
const getUser = () => this.http.get('/user');
function add(a, b) { return a + b; }
arr.map(x => x.id);
arr.filter(item => item.active);

// GOOD — explicit types
const name: string = 'Alice';
const items: number[] = [1, 2, 3];
let count: number = 0;
const getUser = (): Observable<User> => this.http.get<User>('/user');
function add(a: number, b: number): number { return a + b; }
arr.map((x: Item) => x.id);
arr.filter((item: Item) => item.active);
```

## Signals and Angular-Specific

```typescript
// BAD
readonly name = signal('');
readonly count = signal(0);
readonly items = computed(() => this.list().filter(i => i.active));

// GOOD
readonly name: WritableSignal<string> = signal<string>('');
readonly count: WritableSignal<number> = signal<number>(0);
readonly items: Signal<Item[]> = computed((): Item[] => this.list().filter((i: Item) => i.active));
```
